</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D9BB5FFCEFF91FF7AE71FFE8DF98F" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFCEFF91FF7AE71FFBA8FC49" blockId="14.[151,1436,151,1018]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FF7AE71FFEC3FCEA" bold="true" box="[198,312,831,857]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB6B5CFFFCEFF91FEFBE760FDA9FCE9" author="Razowski, J. &amp; Landry, B. &amp; Roque-Albelo, L." box="[327,594,832,858]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="185 - 220" refId="ref35539" refString="Razowski, J. Landry, B. &amp; Roque-Albelo, L. (2008) The Tortricidae (Lepidoptera) of the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 115, 185 - 220." type="journal article" year="2008">
Razowski 
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FE7EE760FE06FCEA" box="[450,509,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
(2008)
</bibRefCitation>
recently described 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FC84E760FC60FCEA" authorityName="Razowski &amp; Landry in Razowski, Landry &amp; Roque-Albelo" authorityYear="2008" box="[824,923,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="johni">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FC84E760FC60FCEA" box="[824,923,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. johni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a single male from the 
<collectingRegion id="49E306DCFFCEFF91FA9CE760FF16FC31" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Galapagos Islands</collectingRegion>
, off the western coast of 
<collectingCountry id="F33088AEFFCEFF91FDAFE748FD8CFC31" box="[531,631,872,898]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. Although I have not examined the 
<typeStatus id="549C769CFFCEFF91FBA7E748FB7EFC31" box="[1051,1157,872,898]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">holotype</typeStatus>
, the images of the adult and genitalia provide ample characters for its identification. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FBE4E7B0FB41FC1A" authorityName="Razowski &amp; Landry in Razowski, Landry &amp; Roque-Albelo" authorityYear="2008" box="[1112,1210,912,937]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="johni">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FBE4E7B0FB41FC1A" box="[1112,1210,912,937]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. johni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FF40E798FE66FC62" box="[252,413,952,977]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macroscia">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FF40E798FE66FC62" box="[252,413,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. macroscia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FD83E798FD59FC62" authorityName="Razowski &amp; Landry in Razowski, Landry &amp; Roque-Albelo" authorityYear="2008" box="[575,674,952,977]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="johni">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FD83E798FD59FC62" box="[575,674,952,977]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. johni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a shorter, more curved basal process of the valva bearing a row of long spines, and the notch at the middle of the uncus is extremely shallow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFCEFF91FDD3E072FC38FBDF" blockId="14.[623,963,1106,1132]" box="[623,963,1106,1132]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FDD3E072FC38FBDF" bold="true" box="[623,963,1106,1132]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
B. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FD76E072FC89FBDF" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Walsingham" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[714,882,1106,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delphinosema">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FD76E072FC89FBDF" bold="true" box="[714,882,1106,1132]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">delphinosema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFCEFF91FF2BE0B2FE8DF98F" blockId="14.[151,1436,1170,1596]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FF72E0B3FE8AFB1F" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Walsingham" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[206,369,1171,1196]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delphinosema">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FF72E0B3FE8AFB1F" box="[206,369,1171,1196]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">delphinosema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group consists of 15 species. The female genitalia are characterized by a pair of sclerotized, slightly rugose lateral bands that extend from a rounded or subquadrate sclerotized perimeter of the ostium. The strongly sclerotized colliculum comprises about 0.5 or more of the ductus bursae in all but 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FAC0E0C3FEE5FA97" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochreoapex">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FAC0E0C3FEE5FA97" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. ochreoapex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FEEBE12BFDFDFA97" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[343,518,1291,1316]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simpliciana">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FEEBE12BFDFDFA97" box="[343,518,1291,1316]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">M. simpliciana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The signum consists of a single, flattened, tongue-shaped or fin-shaped sclerite. Male genitalia in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFCEFF91FE79E113FD93FAFF" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Walsingham" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[453,616,1331,1356]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delphinosema">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFCEFF91FE79E113FD93FAFF" box="[453,616,1331,1356]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">delphinosema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are somewhat variable, but the valva is usually slender in the basal 0.5 and broadened in the distal 0.5, mostly parallel-sided, bearing one or two patches of setae. Usually, one cluster is a circular, dense fascicle of short setae (= cluster of spiniform setae) and the other, usually more basal and more ventral, a patch of more elongate, slender setae (= patch of elongate setae) (see 
<figureCitation id="131CD4BBFFCEFF91FABDE18AFAA2FA77" box="[1281,1369,1450,1476]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="42.[151,269,1930,1954]" captionTargetBox="[221,1374,178,1922]" captionTargetId="figure-56@42.[221,1378,163,1951]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 37. M. ricana, image of USNM slide 85,875; 38. M. ceratovalva, image of USNM slide 124,496; 39. M. bicolorana, image of USNM slide 84,863." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339669/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
). The basal process of the valva is long and slender, usually smooth and slightly curved along the outer surface and elbowed before the middle on the inner surface. Most species have one or more thornlike spines along the dorsum of the phallus.
</paragraph>
